d]] ''(2 Caps/1 Goal)''\n*[[Danny Blair]] ''(7 Caps)''\n*[[George Herd]] ''(5 Caps/1 Goal)''\n*[[Harry Haddock]] ''(6 Caps)''\n*[[Hugh Long]] ''(1 Cap)''\n*[[Jimmy Campbell (footballer born 1921)|Jimmy Campbell]] ''(1 Cap)''\n*[[John Brown (footballer born 1915)|John Brown]] ''(1 Cap)''\n*[[Leslie Johnston]] ''(2 Caps/1 Goal)''\n*[[Tommy Ring]] ''(12 Caps/2 Goals)''\n*[[William Walker (footballer born 1884)|William Walker]] ''(2 Caps)''\n\n|width=\"80\"|&nbsp;\n|valign=\"top\"|\n\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Clyde F.C.}}\n*{{official website|http://www.clydefc.co.uk/}}\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/clyde/default.stm Clyde BBC My Club page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120920032203/http://historicalkits.co.uk/Scottish_Football_League/Clyde/Clyde.htm Historical Kits]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120930025503/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/scottishsecondxicup.htm Scottish 2nd XI Cup]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120924183312/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/scottishfederation2.htm Scottish Football Federation (Second version 1898-99)]\n*[http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/scottishalliance1.htm Scottish Football Alliance (First version 1891-1897)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130130155447/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/scottishalliance3.htm Scottish Football Alliance (Third version 1919-1938)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130924223101/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/scottishalliance4a.htm Scottish Football Alliance (Fifth version 1939-40)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120926204220/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/scottishalliance5.htm Scottish Football Alliance (Sixth version 1956-57)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120913170217/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/scottishreserveleague2.htm Scottish Reserve League (Second version 1909-191)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120926050001/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/scottishreserveleague3.htm Scottish Reserve League (Third version 1938-39)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120605170915/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/scottishreserveleague4.htm Scottish Reserve League (Fourth version 1945-1949)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120917071948/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/scottishreserveleague5.htm Scottish Reserve League (Fifth version 1975-2008)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120925124931/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/scottishreserveleague.htm Scottish (Reserve) League (1955-1975)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120808115948/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/cdiv.htm C Division overview (1949-55)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130130225319/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/combinedreserve1.htm Combined Reserve Football League (First version 1958-1972)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111120024247/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/combinedreserve2.htm Combined Reserve Football League (Second and Third versions 1973-74 & 1975-76)]\n\n<!-- Please do not add unofficial links-->\n\n{{Clyde F.C.}}\n{{Scottish Professional Football League}}\n{{Scottish Football League}}\n{{Football in Glasgow}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}{{EngvarB|date=April 2015}}\n\n[[Category:Clyde F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:Cumbernauld]]\n[[Category:Rutherglen]]\n[[Category:Bridgeton\u2013Calton\u2013Dalmarnock]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1877]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Sport in North Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:Sport in South Lanarkshire]]\n[[Category:1877 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League teams]]\n[[Category:Scottish Cup winners]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League teams]]\n[[Category:Sports team relocations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Clydesdale F.C.|Clydebank F.C.|Vale of Clyde F.C.}}\n{{Infobox football club \n| clubname    = Clyde\n| current     =\n| image       = Clyde FC logo.png\n| image_size  = 200px\n| fullname    = Clyde Football Club\n| nickname    = The Bully Wee\n| founded     = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1877}}\n| ground      = [[Broadwood Stadium]], <br /> [[Cumbernauld]], Scotland\n| capacity    = {{SPFL-stadiums|clyde}}<ref name=\"capacity\">{{cite web|url = http://spfl.co.uk/clubs/clyde/ |title        = Clyde Football Club|publisher=Scottish Professional Football League |accessdate=11 November 2013}}</ref>\n| chairman    = ''Vacant''\n| manager     = [[Danny Lennon]]\n| mgrtitle    =\n| league      = {{Scottish football updater|Clyde}}\n| season      = {{Scottish football updater|Clyde2}}\n| position    = {{Scottish football updater|Clyde3}}\n\n<!-- Home kit -->\n| pattern_la1 =\n| pattern_b1  = _clyde1819h\n| pattern_ra1 =\n| pattern_sh1 =\n| pattern_so1 =\n| leftarm1    = FFFFFF\n| body1       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1   = FFFFFF\n| shorts1     = 000000\n| socks1      = FF0000\n<!-- Away kit -->\n| pattern_la2 =\n| pattern_b2  = _clyde1819a\n| pattern_ra2 =\n| pattern_sh2 =\n| pattern_so2 =\n| leftarm2    = 000000\n| body2       = 000000\n| rightarm2   = 000000\n| shorts2     = 000000\n| socks2      = 000000\n<!-- Third kid -->\n| pattern_la3 =\n| pattern_b3  = _clyde1819t\n| pattern_ra3 =\n| pattern_sh3 =\n| pattern_so3 =\n| leftarm3    = FF0000\n| body3       = FF0000\n| rightarm3   = FF0000\n| shorts3     = FF0000\n| socks3      = FF0000\n| website = http://www.clydefc.co.uk/\n}}\n\n'''Clyde Football Club''' are a Scottish semi-professional [[Association football|football]] club based in [[Cumbernauld]], [[North Lanarkshire]] who play in [[Scottish League One]]. Formed in 1877 at the [[River Clyde]] in [[Glasgow]], since 1994 the team have played their home games at [[Broadwood Stadium]]. Their biggest accomplishment was winning the [[Scottish Cup]] on three occasions: [[1939 Scottish Cup Final|1939]], [[1955 Scottish Cup Final|1955]] and [[1958 Scottish Cup Final|1958]]; they reached the final a further three times, all during a long period based at [[Shawfield Stadium|Shawfield]]. They have not played in the top division of Scottish football since 1975.\n\n==History==\n===1877\u20131898===\nThe Clyde Football Club was founded and played on the banks of the [[River Clyde]] at Barrowfield. Documentary evidence from the SFA and indeed match reports in the [[Glasgow]] press clearly show it all began in 1877, and the thread continues unbroken to this day.\n\nHere's how the [[Scottish Football Association|SFA]] recorded Clyde's origins:\n\n{{Quotation|\"Clyde:- Founded 1877; Membership 50; Grounds (private), [[Barrowfield Park]], on the banks of the Clyde; ten minutes walk from Bridgeton Cross; Club House on grounds; Colours, White & Blue. Hon. Secretary, John D. Graham, 24 Monteith Row.\"}}\n\nSitting on the edge of [[Bridgeton, Glasgow|Bridgeton]], Barrowfield Park lay in a triangle of land enclosed by Carstairs Street, Colvend Street and the river Clyde. The area was an intense mix of chemical, engineering and textile work with a high population density to provide the labour. Although no stadium photographs have emerged, it appears the ground consisted of a grandstand running north\u2013south, a pavilion and tennis courts at the southern end and a bicycle track surrounding the pitch.\n\nToday this area is dotted with industrial units, but also contains a large grassed area, so it may be possible to stand upon a corner of the original Barrowfield pitch. Barrowfield got initially shared with a short-lived team called Albatross.\n\nThe club founded then has no resemblance to a modern professional football club. Clyde F.C. was a private members club more akin to a present-day golf or bowling club. Clyde's Secretary, John Graham, was also a noted rower and it seems the club had other sporting and cultural activities besides football.\n\nThe first mention of Clyde was in Monday's [[Evening Times]] of 17 September 1877:\n\n{{Quotation|\"Clyde v T. Lanark\nClyde opened their season at Barrowfield with a match against the 3rd Lanark Volunteers. In the end, the 3rd were victors by three goals to 1.\"}}\n\nThis concise report was typical at the time as the sport was of little significance and football competed with racing, bowling and quoting for the limited column space available.\n\nAlthough most fixtures were informal, the [[Scottish Cup]] had existed since 1873. Soon there would also be the [[Glasgow Merchants Charity Cup]] and the [[Glasgow Cup]] which in their time were hotly contested major competitions. Clyde entered the 1st Round of the Scottish Cup on 29 September 1877 along with one hundred and one other teams. [[Third Lanark A.C.|Third Lanark]] were the visitors once again, and triumphed 1\u20130.\n\nClyde joined the [[Scottish Football League]] in 1891, its second edition. Following acceptance, [[Vale of Leven F.C.|Vale of Leven]] provided the opposition for Clyde's first League fixture on Saturday, 15 August 1891. In a dream introduction to the format Clyde triumphed 10\u20133, and a mid-table finish saw the club complete a confident season in League football. While it was an undoubted success, Barrowfield revealed its limitations and could not cope with the crowds as many gained illegal entry. Opposition teams complained about the facilities, and it was clear that Clyde would have to do something to appease the League.\n\nThe club endured a terrible [[1897\u201398 in Scottish football|final season]] at Barrowfield, finishing bottom of Division 1 with only 5 points, but remained in the top division. The last action at Barrowfield was a friendly against crack opposition in the form of [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on 30 April 1898, ending in a 3\u20133 draw.<ref>[http://www.thestatcat.co.uk/Match.aspx?MatchID=5419&LU=S&LUID=19 Match Details], TheStatCat</ref>\n\n===1899\u20131919===\nClyde said farewell to Barrowfield in the spring of 1898. Directly across the river between the Glasgow neighbourhood of [[Oatlands, Glasgow|Oatlands]] and the [[Lanarkshire]] town of [[Rutherglen]] lay some open ground known as [[Shawfield]], and Clyde transformed from Brigtonians to Shawfielders. With a new League season only a matter of months away, Clyde had the monumental task of transforming and enclosing the area into a venue suitable for first-class football. The move was primarily financed by the club becoming incorporated and issuing shares in \"The Clyde Football Club Limited\". By the eve of the new season, Clyde F.C. Ltd had an enclosed area of about {{convert|9|acre|ha}}. A grandstand seating 1500 was nearing completion and embankment works around the pitch were well underway. The Clyde directors of the time wildly estimated a final capacity of 100,000.\n\n[[File: ClydeFC League Performance.svg|thumb|right|Chart of historic table positions of Clyde in the League.]]\n[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], the neighbours from up the road, were the inaugural opposition at [[Shawfield Stadium]] on 27 August 1898. A healthy crowd of 10,000 turned up to see a goalless draw and return gate receipts of \u00a3203. The [[1899\u20131900 in Scottish football|1899\u20131900]] season ended with another bottom-placed finish, and this time, relegation. By [[1901\u201302 in Scottish football|1901\u201302]],the club had sunk to the bottom of the lower division.\n\nMatters took a turn for the better in the [[1903\u201304 in Scottish football|1903\u201304 season]]. Clyde finished 2nd in Division Two but were not elected to Division One (automatic promotion/relegation did not appear until 1921). They also won a supplementary competition called the [[Glasgow and West of Scotland Football League|Glasgow & West of Scotland League]] the following season. The promotion was again denied in [[1904\u201305 in Scottish football|season 1904\u201305]], with Clyde the Division Two champions, but was finally granted the [[1905\u201306 in Scottish football|following season]]. The years up to [[World War I]] would be far more successful and probably represent the most consistent period of success for the club.\n\nA 3rd place in Division One in [[1908\u201309 in Scottish football|season 1908\u201309]], only three points behind champions Celtic, put Clyde firmly on the map of Scottish football. The semi-final of the [[Scottish Cup]] was also reached for the first time only to be thwarted by Celtic after a replay. International honours were also awarded to Clyde players for the first time this season: [[William Walker (footballer, born 1884)|William 'Shoogly' Walker]]  represented [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] against [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]] (5\u20130), while the opposition included his team-mate, [[Jack Kirwan]].\n\nFor five seasons until the war began, Clyde was at the top end of Division One and reached the [[Scottish Cup]] final in [[1909\u201310 Scottish Cup#Final|1910]] and [[1911\u201312 Scottish Cup#Final|1912]]. The former of these finals was especially disappointing. For eighty-three minutes Clyde (McTurk; Watson & Blair; Walker, [[Tom McAteer|McAteer]] & Robertson; Stirling & McCartney; Chalmers; Jackson & Booth) held a 2\u20130 lead with goals from Chalmers and Booth and looked sure to win. With the Cup in sight, nerves got the better of Clyde and Robertson fluffed a clearance off Blair and into his net. Dogged [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] fought all the way and salvaged the game in the last minute with an equaliser from Langlands. The replay was far more cagey an affair and ended goalless after [[extra time]] but with Dundee looking physically stronger. The third game was again a tight affair with Clyde scoring after only three minutes through Chalmers. Dundee equalised before the interval and with Clyde's energy sapped, [[John Hunter (footballer, born 1878)|John \"Sailor\" Hunter]] blasted Dundee to victory.\n\nThe 1912 final saw Celtic trump the ''Bully Wee'' once again with a 2\u20130 victory, another third-place finish in the League being the only consolation. Still undaunted, Clyde reached the semi-final back in 1912\u201313, but the jinx struck again and after a replay [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] squeezed into the final.\n\nClyde had something to cheer about during this period of near misses as they clinched the Glasgow Merchants Charity Cup in 1910 and the Glasgow Cup in 1915. It is easy to deride these competitions as second rate, but they were fought for just as hard as the Scottish Cup, and indeed all six competitors (Celtic, Clyde, [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]], [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]], [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and Third Lanark) were more often than not resident in Division One.\n\nA severe blow was dealt in September 1914 as fire destroyed the grandstand, and with it much of the club's early history. Officials, players and fans had little time to dwell upon the calamity as the war began in November. The Scottish League decided to continue playing even though there was intense moral pressure on every young man to sign up for 'King & Country'. Besides, football crowds provided a fertile recruitment ground, and the games themselves kept morale high. Many players joined up \u2013 some never returned, such as C. Clunas (2nd [[Royal Fusiliers]]), T. Cranston ([[Black Watch]] ) and W. Sharp (1st Battalion [[Royal Scots]]) \u2013 and teams like Clyde found it increasingly difficult to field competitive sides  and the League eventually reduced back to a single division.\n\n===1920\u20131945===\nClyde managed to sustain football through the difficult war years, and peacetime presented new challenges. The Scottish League continued through [[1919\u201320 in Scottish football|1919\u201321]] with only one division. Division Two was restarted in [[1921\u201322 in Scottish football|1921\u201322]] with a very crucial difference: automatic promotion and relegation was adopted, and while the benefits were evident for ambitious teams, the financial penalties for falling out of the top tier were extremely severe.\n\nRelegated in 1923\u201324, Clyde spent two seasons in Division Two playing against the likes of [[Armadale F.C.|Armadale]], [[Arthurlie F.C.|Arthurlie]], [[Bathgate F.C.|Bathgate]], [[Bo'ness F.C.|Bo'ness]], [[Broxburn F.C.|Broxburn]], [[King's Park F.C.|king's Park]], [[Nithsdale Wanderers F.C.|Nithsdale Wanderers]] and [[St Bernard's F.C.|St Bernard's]]. Escape via automatic promotion was achieved in the [[1925\u201326 in Scottish football|1925\u201326 season]] and coincided with the demise of Division Three and many of the smaller teams returning to other leagues and Junior football.\n\nThis upswing in Clyde's fortunes was demonstrated by winning the Glasgow Cup for the second time in 1926 with a 2\u20131 victory over Celtic. Now that Clyde was back in the top flight, could they stay there? Until the outbreak of World War II in 1939, the answer was a resounding \"yes\" as the club maintained a respectable mid-table status. [[Danny Blair]] was a prominent international full back of this era and [[Billy Boyd (footballer)|Billy Boyd]] became Clyde's top marksman with 32 goals in season 1932\u201333, also earning two international caps.\n\nClyde and financial problems were never far apart, and liquidation was again narrowly averted around 1930. The club needed to find an answer to their money problems, and it lay right in front of them. Greyhound and other animal racing were booming in the late 1920s, and several clubs saw this as a way to supplement their income. A company offered to lease Shawfield in 1926 and also give a percentage of the gate money to Clyde. It seemed too good to be accurate, and it proved to be so. Animal racing was forbidden in the deeds of Shawfield and the League was very set against greyhound racing in general.\n\nHowever, Clyde at that time had a very cunning and dogged chairman called John McMahon. He would not let the idea go, and after years of wrangling, a solution has arrived. The Shawfield Greyhound Racing Company Limited started racing in 1932 and a few years later purchased the stadium from Clyde. Largely financed and owned by Clyde's directors, at a stroke the club had secured its future and found an additional source of revenue. On the other hand, Clyde had sold Shawfield to another party (however close at the time) and would never be able to raise money using the land asset as collateral. Although it would not have repercussions until the 1980s, Clyde were tenants at the mercy of whoever owned Shawfield.\n\nJanuary 1939 saw Clyde at home to [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] in the 1st Round of the Scottish Cup. A 2\u20130 victory sent Clyde on their way. The next tie saw a challenging trip to Dundee, and a goalless draw ensued. Four days later, Clyde squeezed past the [[Dens Park]] men with a 1\u20130 victory. [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]], and [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] were the formidable 3rd Round opponents. Despite fourteen League titles and six Cup victories between 1920 and 1939, Rangers were no match for the ''Bully Wee'' as they crashed to a 4\u20131 defeat. [[Willie Martin (Scottish footballer)|Willie Martin]], Clyde's prolific centre forward, scored all four goals and set a record for an opposition at Ibrox. Returning to Shawfield for the 4th Round, Clyde narrowly defeated neighbours [[Third Lanark A.C.|Third Lanark]] 1\u20130. Suddenly it was semi-final time once again with [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] standing between Clyde and another final. Although disadvantaged by playing the tie in Edinburgh at [[Tynecastle Stadium|Tynecastle]], Clyde again triumphed with a 1\u20130 victory.<ref name=39cup/>\n\n[[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] provided Clyde's opposition on 22 April 1939. They had scored far more goals on the way to [[Hampden Park|Hampden]] and were installed as favourites. Clyde ([[John Brown (footballer born 1915)|Brown]]; Kirk and Hickie; Beaton, [[Eddie Falloon|Falloon]] and [[Ned Weir|Weir]]; Robertson and [[John Gillies (footballer)|Gillies]]; Martin; Noble and [[Dougie Wallace (footballer)|Wallace]]) had other ideas though. Winning the toss and with a strong wind behind them, Motherwell began very strongly and unsettled Clyde with Brown seeing plenty of action. Riding the storm, Clyde settled and scored the vital goal after thirty minutes. Robertson sped down the right and crossed to Wallace. The forward gathered the ball and smashed the ball into the roof of the net. Motherwell replied with more pressure but could not find a goal before the interval. In the second period, Martin quickly doubled Clyde's advantage with an opportunist's strike. The fight went from Motherwell and Clyde scored an extra two in the closing minutes. Motherwell's keeper blocked Noble's first strike at goal, but he swept home the rebound. Barely a minute later Noble supplied a cross for Martin to complete the scoring and seal a 4\u20130 victory. After so many attempts and so much heartache the Cup was finally won.<ref name=39cup>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48328186 Scottish Cup final: 80th anniversary for Clyde side that held the trophy longest], BBC Sport, 27 May 2019</ref>\n\nAlthough the joy of victory was unconfined, it was tempered against a background of imminent [[World War II|war with Nazi Germany]]. The [[1939\u201340 in Scottish football|1939\u201340 season]] had hardly begun when war was declared and the Scottish League was suspended, and all players' contracts declared void. After the initial panic, unofficial leagues restarted with an East/West regional split. The geographical separation saw Clyde join the [[Southern Football League (Scotland)|Southern League]] where they finished runners-up and only three points behind eventual champions Rangers during the [[1940\u201341 in Scottish football|1940\u201341 season]]. Clyde performed relatively well during wartime football in both league and cup football.\n\n===1946\u20131969===\nThe team showed steady league form just after the war and reached a fourth [[Scottish Cup]] final in [[1948\u201349 Scottish Cup|1948\u201349]]. In only the fourth edition of the competition since Clyde won it in 1938\u201339, their opponents [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] ran out comfortable 4\u20131 winners in front of a crowd of 108,000 at [[Hampden Park|Hampden]], with Peter Galletly scoring Clyde's consolation goal.<ref name=1946to1970>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/club/history/post-war/ | title=Club History 1946\u20131969 | publisher=Clyde FC | accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 1950s began with relegation from [[Scottish Division One|Division A]] in [[1950\u201351 Scottish Division One|1950\u201351]], returning at the first attempt as [[Scottish Division Two|Division B]] champions in [[1951\u201352 Scottish Division Two|1951\u201352]]. The team repeated the feat in [[1955\u201356 Scottish Division One|1955\u201356]] and [[1956\u201357 Scottish Division Two|1956\u201357]]. Each occasion saw the team bounce back to solid finishes in Division A. Floodlighting was introduced at Shawfield in March 1954. The first opposition was [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] in a [[Exhibition match|friendly]] match. Huddersfield won 3\u20132. Cup success came readily in the 1950s. They won the [[Scottish Cup]] in [[1954\u201355 Scottish Cup|1954\u201355]] and [[1957\u201358 Scottish Cup|1957\u201358]] and were beaten semi-finalists in [[1955\u201356 Scottish Cup|1955\u201356]] and [[1959\u201360 Scottish Cup|1959\u201360]]. They also reached [[Scottish League Cup]] semi-finals in [[1956\u201357 Scottish League Cup|1956\u201357]] and [[1957\u201358 Scottish League Cup|1957\u201358]], but lost on both occasions to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref name=1946to1970/>\n\nThe route to the 1954\u201355 Final began with three straight home victories in the competition against [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]] (3\u20130), [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]] (3\u20131) and [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] (5\u20130). [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] provided Clyde's semi-final opponents. After a 2\u20132 draw at [[Easter Road]], a solitary goal in the replay sent Clyde into the final. On 23 April 1955 at [[Hampden Park|Hampden]] in front of over 96,000, Celtic, installed as firm favourites, provided the opposition in the final, in a match that was also the first to be televised live.<ref name=1946to1970/> Without forward [[Billy McPhail]] and goalkeeper [[William Wilson (goalkeeper)|William Wilson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qosfc.com/AboutQueens/QueensLegends/tabid/115/Default.aspx |title=1955 Aberdeen v Clyde SC SF |publisher=QOS FC |accessdate=3 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917025553/http://qosfc.com/AboutQueens/QueensLegends/tabid/115/Default.aspx |archivedate=17 September 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> Clyde lined up:- Hewkins, [[Albie Murphy|Murphy]] & [[Harry Haddock|Haddock]]; [[Ralph Granville|Granville]], Anderson & [[Davie Laing|Laing]]; [[John Divers (footballer born 1931)|Divers]] & [[Archie Robertson (footballer)|Robertson]]; [[Ally Hill|Hill]]; [[George Brown (footballer born 1928)|Brown]] & [[Tommy Ring|Ring]]. Celtic took the lead in a scrappy match and were three minutes from victory until Archie Robertson scored direct from a corner kick to earn a replay. A crowd of over 68,000 gathered for the replay, which was a more open affair. Clyde, with the same line up, won 1\u20130 and their second Scottish Cup with Tommy Ring's second half strike.<ref name=1946to1970/>\n\nBack at Hampden again on 26 April 1958 in front of a crowd of 94,000 to face a powerful [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] team, Clyde lined up:- [[Tommy McCulloch (footballer, born 1934)|McCulloch]], [[Albie Murphy|Murphy]] & [[Harry Haddock|Haddock]]; Walters, Finlay & Clinton; [[George Herd|Herd]] & Currie; [[John Coyle|Coyle]]; [[Archie Robertson (footballer)|Robertson]] & [[Tommy Ring|Ring]]. Johnny Coyle's deflected shot in poor conditions gave Clyde a 1\u20130 win and a second Scottish Cup in four seasons and third overall. A fourth-place league finish and a [[Scottish League Cup]] semi-final appearance completed an impressive season in [[1957\u201358 in Scottish football|1957\u201358]].<ref name=1946to1970/> Haddock, Robertson and Coyle were selected in the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]] [[1958 FIFA World Cup squads#.C2.A0Scotland|Scotland squad]]. Dan Currie was selected in the provisional Scotland [[1958 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] squad, but ultimately did not make the final cut.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.scottishleague.net/forum/viewtopic.php?f=3&t=3372&hilit=clyde+football+club&sid=25df8e2bd45e546d9714f30414353ec9&start=15 | title=Called Up But Not Capped | publisher=ScottishLeague.net | date=5 September 2012 | accessdate=28 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960, Clyde gained entry into the [[Anglo-Franco-Scottish Friendship Cup|Friendship Cup]]. It was an inter-League competition between four clubs each from [[Football in England|England]], [[Football in France|France]] and [[Football in Scotland|Scotland]], with results aggregated to provide the 'best' League. It proved to be an unpopular format and ended in 1962. For the record, Clyde was drawn against [[RC Lens]] of France and beat them 4\u20130 away and 2\u20131 at [[Shawfield Stadium|Shawfield]]. The club began the 1960s as a yo-yo club. Relegations in [[1960\u201361 Scottish Division One|1960\u201361]] and [[1962\u201363 Scottish Division One|1962\u201363]] were followed by immediate promotions in [[1961\u201362 Scottish Division Two|1961\u201362]] and [[1963\u201364 Scottish Division Two|1963\u201364]], the former as Division Two champions.<ref name=1946to1970/>\n\nThe [[1966\u201367 in Scottish football|1966\u201367]] season led Clyde to their highest league finish in forty-five years and another Scottish Cup semi-final appearance. Competing largely as a part-time team, Clyde finished third behind the [[Old Firm]] clubs. After producing a wonderful season of football that has marked the high tide in the club's fortunes to date, [[UEFA competitions|European football]] will forever love denying itself. The [[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]] had a rule that stipulated only one team per city could enter. Clyde argued that they were not from Glasgow; they were from [[Rutherglen]]. However UEFA denied this argument citing Clyde's non-membership of the Lanarkshire FA and their participation in the [[Glasgow Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sundaypost.com/opinion/r-i-p-davie-white/|title=R.I.P Davie White - Sunday Post|author=|date=27 July 2013|website=sundaypost.com|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref> Rangers had that position. Another League Cup semi-final was reached in [[1968\u201369 Scottish League Cup|1968\u201369]].<ref name=1946to1970/>\n\nAs the 1960s came to a close, Clyde was competing rather comfortably in the top division. It was a different story on the terraces with Glasgow's [[slum clearance]] programme hitting attendances hard. Large swathes of housing in [[Bridgeton, Glasgow|Bridgeton]], [[Dalmarnock]], [[Gorbals]], [[Oatlands, Glasgow|Oatlands]] and [[Rutherglen]] were being demolished with the inhabitants decanted away to other parts of the city and beyond. Clyde's core support was drawn from these areas, and many of them have never returned to follow the team.<ref name=1946to1970/>\n\n===1970\u20131993===\nThe club began the 1970s as in previous decades, with the threat of relegation of hanging around. In an attempt to quit the city, there was an attempted merger with [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]],who were in dire financial trouble and had resigned from the [[Scottish Football League|Scottish League]]. After the move floundered as quickly as it arose, Hamilton quickly rejoined the League. Less than a year later, [[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]] of [[Scottish Division Two|Division Two]] made an audacious bid to merge with Clyde in [[Scottish Division One|Division One]] at the time in return for a cash settlement. The Scottish League quickly quashed the move, after viewing it as Dumbarton trying to gain back-door entry into the top division.<ref name=1970to1993>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/club/history/changes/ | title=Club History 1970\u20131993 | publisher=Clyde FC | accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter relegation in [[1971\u201372 Scottish Division One|1971\u201372]], many club legends such as [[Harry Glasgow]], Sam Hastings, [[Tommy McCulloch (footballer, born 1934)|Tommy McCulloch]], Graham McFarlane and [[Eddie Mulheron]] moved on. Clyde did recover and won promotion as Division Two champions in [[1972\u201373 Scottish Division Two|1972\u201373]]. Two years in the top division until another relegation in [[1974\u201375 Scottish Division One|1974\u201375]] would be their last in the top division to date. The [[Scottish Premier Division|Premier Division]] was introduced ahead of the season [[1975\u201376 in Scottish football|1975\u201376]] as the new top division, with inclusion based upon league position. A poor 16th-place finish in Division One in season 1974\u201375 meant Clyde was never in contention. The club now found themselves back in the second tier, now known as the [[Scottish First Division|First Division]].<ref name=1970to1993/>\n\nThe club found a new role, discovering and developing talent before selling it on. Shawfield was the starting point for future [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] internationalists like [[Steve Archibald]], [[Ian Ferguson (footballer born 1967)|Ian Ferguson]] and [[Pat Nevin]]. Problems on and off the pitch saw Clyde move into freefall. After finishing bottom of the First Division in [[1975\u201376 Scottish First Division|1975\u201376]], they found themselves in the [[Scottish Second Division|Second Division]], the third tier, for the season [[1976\u201377 Scottish Second Division|1976\u201377]]. They only could muster a seventh-place finish. In a decade Clyde had gone from the third best team in Scotland to a single spot above the finishing last in the [[Scottish football league system]]. Towards the end of the season, [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] legend [[Billy McNeill]] took charge but left for Aberdeen after only a few months at the helm. The club then turned to the relatively unknown [[Craig Brown (footballer, born 1940)|Craig Brown]], and he had immediate success as the team won the Second Division in [[1977\u201378 Scottish Second Division|1977\u201378]].<ref name=1970to1993/>\n\nProblems were arising at Shawfield. The stadium was falling into a state of disrepair, and the grounds were not well maintained. By the late 1970s, Shawfield came into the hands of the [[Greyhound Racing Association]] (GRA). [[Greyhound racing]] had been in decline since 1963 when off-course betting was allowed. To compensate for this, the GRA had transformed itself into a property company and had a policy of acquiring and redeveloping dog tracks for commercial and residential uses.<ref name=1970to1993/>\n\nRelegation from the First Division in [[1979\u201380 Scottish First Division|1979\u201380]] was followed by another promotion as Second Division champions in [[1981\u201382 Scottish First Division|1981\u201382]]. Shawfield eventually came on the open market in 1983 with a \u00a3500,000 price tag. The club was served with a notice to quit Shawfield by 1986. [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]] provided the final opposition at Shawfield on 28 April 1986. Clyde claimed a 4\u20132 win. The unpopular but necessary decision was taken to ground-share with city rivals [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]. Clyde spent five unhappy seasons at Firhill, and there was a sense of relief when Clyde departed. The club was grateful for the use of Firhill, but there was an underlying sense of being tolerated as an inconvenient annoyance.<ref name=1970to1993/>\n\nThe 'Gypsy Army' reference came into being as Clyde supporters sought pride and solace during the club's homeless years. The club then negotiated a ground-share at [[Douglas Park]] with Hamilton Academical, where Clyde resided for two and a half seasons as plans were developed and implemented to build a new home in [[Cumbernauld]].<ref name=1970to1993/> Meanwhile, on the field, relegation from the First Division in [[1990\u201391 Scottish First Division|1990\u201391]], was followed by promotion again as Second Division champions in [[1992\u201393 Scottish First Division|1992\u201393]] and an immediate relegation in [[1993\u201394 Scottish First Division|1993\u201394]].  However, this continued the tradition of the yo-yo existence the club had become known for at certain times in previous decades.\n\n===1994\u2013present===\n\nThe Cumbernauld Development Corporation was keen to have a sports stadium and professional football team to promote the town, and [[Cumbernauld]], with a 50,000+ population, seemed fertile ground on which to grow new support. A new site called \"[[Broadwood Stadium|Broadwood]]\" was to have an integrated business, housing and leisure development with a football stadium at the heart of it. With the help of Football Trust backing, two modern stands began to emerge during the early 1990s.\n\nThe Scottish League unusually granted permission for Clyde to switch grounds mid-season, and former landlords, [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]], were the inaugural opposition on 5 February 1994. A capacity crowd of 6000 watched as Clyde lost to the ''Accies'' 2\u20130.\n\nClyde dropped to the third tier of football, and in 1998 they almost fell into the lowest reaches of Senior football. However, this was enough for the new chairman, Billy Carmichael, to introduce changes. Ronnie MacDonald got appointed as manager, having worked at [[Maryhill F.C.|Maryhill Juniors]]. MacDonald signed a whole squad from the Junior ranks, and within two seasons Clyde had gained promotion.  Subsequently, Allan Maitland won promotion to the [[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]] in 1999.\n\nThe [[2003\u201304 in Scottish football|2003\u201304 season]] saw Clyde atop the League and looking set for the [[Scottish Premier League|SPL]]. But Broadwood did not comply with SPL requirements and crucially Clyde was on the brink of being petitioned by their creditors and liquidated. While the chairman's fortune was well spent on players' wages, very little else got serviced. The SPL relented and said Clyde could join them if the fourth stand got built. North Lanarkshire Council started the groundworks and then abruptly halted them as they became aware of Clyde's financial plight. Plan B, playing at [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]], was investigated.  In the event, a draw with [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] and a home loss to [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] meant that Clyde missed out on promotion.\n\nThe Clyde Supporters' Trust formed during the [[2003\u201304 in Scottish football|2003\u201304 season]]. Early that season some concerned fans met knowing that the chairman could not keep financing the Club indefinitely.  The timing of the Trust's formation coincided with Clyde's failure to gain promotion, and the chairman sought to sell his majority shareholding. Following lengthy negotiations, a consortium of the Trust and traditional investors increased the majority shareholding for a nominal sum. The Clyde Development Consortium took control of funds gathered by fans and investors and used it to finance the Club through a CVA to clear the debts. In June 2005 the CVA was completed, and Clyde was mostly debt free.\n\nIn a season, [[2005\u201306 in Scottish football|2005\u201306]], that saw Clyde lead 2\u20131 from 1\u20130 behind at [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in a [[2005\u201306 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] tie with 17 minutes left before a goalkeeping error gifted Rangers an equalizer, with Clyde going on to lose in extra time,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2005/09/20/1513/ | title=Rangers 5\u20132 Clyde (AET) | publisher=Clyde FC | date=20 September 2005 | accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref> the other half of the [[Old Firm]], [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] visited Broadwood in the [[Scottish Cup]] on 8 January 2006. Celtic were such heavy favourites that the game was presented as a gentle introduction for their new signing, [[Roy Keane]]. Clyde, however, won 2\u20131. The goal scorers for Clyde were [[Eddie Malone]] and [[Craig Bryson]] whilst Celtic's goal scorer was [[Maciej Zurawski]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2006/01/08/1624/ | title=Clyde 2\u20131 Celtic | publisher=Clyde FC | date=8 January 2006 | accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref> Clyde reached the [[2006 Scottish Challenge Cup Final|2006 Challenge Cup Final]], their first final for 48 years, since their [[Scottish Cup]] success in 1958.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2006/09/27/1886/ | title=Clyde 3\u20131 Morton | date=27 September 2006 | accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref> They lost the game 5\u20134 on a penalty shootout, after the game finished 1\u20131 following extra time.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2006/11/12/1925/ | title=No Cup of Joy | date=12 November 2006 | accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] [[Captain (association football)|captain]] [[Colin Hendry]] was appointed manager in summer 2007. On 14 August of that year, Clyde history was made when [[Michael Doherty (footballer)|Michael Doherty]] became the youngest person ever to play for Clyde in a competitive match,<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.hamiltonadvertiser.co.uk/news/2007/08/23/michael-is-the-bully-wee-x2019-s-youngest-star-50144-19677693/|title = Michael is the Bully Wee's youngest star|publisher = hamiltonadvertiser.co.uk|date = 23 August 2007|accessdate = 24 July 2012}}</ref> a feat later broken by [[Connor Stevenson]] in a league match at [[Palmerston Park|Palmerston]] on 25 April 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2009/04/27/3133/ | title=Connor Makes Clyde History | publisher=Clyde FC | date=27 April 2009 | accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHendry resigned in January 2008, due to family reasons.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11781_3058902,00.html|title = Hendry leaves Clyde|publisher = skysports.com|date = 18 January 2008|accessdate = 24 July 2012}}</ref> Former [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] defender [[John Brown (footballer born 1962)|John 'Bomber' Brown]] replaced him as manager. Clyde entered the final game of the season needing to better Morton's result to avoid getting forced into the playoffs. Clyde won their game 3\u20130, but in a cruel twist of fate, Morton won their own game by the same scoreline, sending Clyde into a two-legged play-off with Second Division side [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]. Clyde lost the first leg 2\u20131 and at 3\u20131 down in the home second leg looked as good as relegated. However, a thrilling fightback saw Clyde level at 5\u20135 on aggregate (4\u20133 on the day) before adding another goal in [[extra time]] to progress. Home and away victories over [[Airdrie United F.C.|Airdrie United]] in the play-off final then secured First Division football at Broadwood for another season.\n\nHowever, the following season Clyde finished bottom of the [[Scottish Football League First Division|First Division]] and got relegated to the [[Scottish Football League Second Division|Second Division]]. Meanwhile, off the park, financial problems were once again apparent. In a hope to try and avoid administration in June 2009, Clyde terminated the contracts of the entire first-team squad, with only youngsters remaining under contract at the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/clyde/8093850.stm|title=Clyde scrap contracts to survive|work=BBC Sport|date=10 June 2009|accessdate=10 June 2009}}</ref> The squad for 2009\u201310 was rebuilt on a drastically reduced budget with a repeat of open trials which were successful in 2005. However early results were not good, and the board appointed [[Neil Watt]] as Director of Football and [[John McCormack (footballer, born 1955)|John McCormack]] as first team coach. After a brief upturn in results, Clyde went six games without a win, and on Saturday 21 November, with the team sitting three points adrift at the bottom of the Second Division, it was announced that John Brown had left his position as manager.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2009/11/21/3358/|title = Brown Leaves|date = 21 November 2009|accessdate = 21 November 2009}}</ref> On Monday 5 April John McCormack was sacked by Clyde.<ref>{{cite news | URL = http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2010/04/05/3511/ | title = Club Statement: John McCormack | publisher = Clyde FC | date = 5 April 2010 | accessdate = 23 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nMore history was made in a home match with [[Peterhead F.C.|Peterhead]] on 17 April 2010, when Willie Sawyers scored after only eight seconds, which became the fastest Clyde goal ever recorded.<ref>{{cite Web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2010/04/20/3528/ | title=Willie Makes Clyde History | date=20 April 2010 | accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref> Despite this, the club was subsequently relegated for the second season in a row, dropping down to the [[Scottish Football League Third Division|Third Division]] where they made a disastrous start to the campaign, including an 8\u20131 thrashing at the hands of [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]]. On Wednesday 2 February 2011, Stuart Millar was sacked as manager of Clyde.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/clyde/9384699.stm|title=Clyde FC sack manager Stuart Millar after poor run|work=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2011|accessdate=2 February 2011}}</ref> They finished 10th in the Third Division, which at 42nd and last place overall is the lowest position in the Scottish league system.\n\nOn 20 April 2013 Clyde's owners voted to move to [[East Kilbride]] and rename the club EK Clyde FC,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22232813|title=Clyde approve move to East Kilbride and name change|work=BBC Sport|date=20 April 2013|accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/222462-fan-owners-of-clyde-football-club-vote-in-favour-of-moving-to-east-kilbride/|title=Fan-owned Clyde FC vote for new name and new East Kilbride home|publisher=stv sport|date=23 April 2013|accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref> however this plan would later be abandoned. The 2013\u201314 season saw a significant improvement on the field when a [[Scottish League One|League One]] play-off spot was secured in the penultimate league match of the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2014/04/26/4629/|title=Clyde 4\u20130 Albion Rovers|work=Clyde FC|date=26 April 2014|accessdate=7 May 2014}}</ref> In the previous six seasons Clyde had finished in the bottom two positions of every league campaign. However, the club missed out on promotion after a play-off semi-final defeat on penalties to [[East Fife F.C.|East Fife]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27326178|title=East Fife 2\u20131 Clyde (Agg 2\u20132; 7\u20136 on pens)|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=10 May 2014|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref> Gordon Young became the first Clyde player to score with their first touch on their club debut in a match against [[Elgin City F.C.|Elgin City]] on 1 March 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2014/03/01/4581/|title=Clyde 4\u20130 Elgin City|work=Clyde FC|date=1 March 2014|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2014/03/03/4585/|title=Gordon Creates History|work=Clyde FC|date=3 March 2014|accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuffy resigned as manager of Clyde on 19 May 2014 to take up the vacant managerial post at [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27477576|title=Jim Duffy leaves Clyde to join Morton|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=19 May 2014|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref> while John Taylor, a member of the boardroom since 1986, and the club's longest serving director had stepped down in April.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2014/04/27/4631/|title=John Steps Down|work=Clyde FC|date=27 April 2014|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, the club were declared officially debt free, having accumulated an unsustainable debt of \u00a31.4&nbsp;million as a result of the club's failed promotion bid to the [[Scottish Premier League|SPL]] during season [[2003\u201304 in Scottish football|2003\u201304]], with the burden of debt having weighed heavily on the shoulders of the club for the next decade.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2014/10/23/4759/|title=Clyde FC is Debt Free|work=Clyde FC|date=23 October 2014|accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref> Scott Durie became the first Clyde player to play every single minute of every competitive match in a season, during the [[2014\u201315 in Scottish football|2014\u201315]] season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2015/05/03/4896/ | title=Scott Achieves Unique Feat | publisher=Clyde FC | date=3 May 2015 | accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nFormer Rangers, Blackburn and Scotland midfielder [[Barry Ferguson]] was appointed as player-manager of Clyde in June 2014 and took the club to a 6th-place finish in his first season in charge. Ferguson officially retired as a player towards the end of that season. The following year, Clyde finished 3rd in League Two but got beaten in the playoff final. On 25 February 2017 with the club in 8th place in League Two after a 1\u20130 defeat to Annan Athletic and with no realistic prospect of gaining promotion after a ten-match winless run, Ferguson resigned as manager of Clyde, with his assistant [[Bob Malcolm]] taking interim charge of the side until a new manager was appointed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2017/02/26/5420/#.WLPwO_nyiUk |title=Tuesday Night's Match |publisher=Clyde FC |date=26 February 2017 |accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter nine years in the bottom tier of Scottish football, at the end of the 2018\u201319 season Clyde achieved promotion to Scottish League One, beating Annan Athletic 2\u20131 on aggregate to win the promotion play-off final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48236302|title=Clyde 2\u20130 Annan Athletic|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=18 May 2019|accessdate=5 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Grounds==\n[[Image:shawfield 2.jpg|thumb|Shawfield in 1985]]\n\n===Barrowfield Park===\nClyde has had five home grounds since they formed in 1877. The first of these was [[Barrowfield Park]], situated on the banks of the River Clyde between the Glasgow neighbourhoods of [[Bridgeton, Glasgow|Bridgeton]] and [[Dalmarnock]].\n\n===Shawfield Stadium===\nBy 1898, Barrowfield became too small in capacity to deal with the large crowds of spectators. The club then moved across the river to build a new stadium, which would be known as [[Shawfield Stadium]].\n\nA crowd of 10,000 saw the first match at Shawfield against [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]. In 1908, a group of 52,000 gathered for a game against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], which remains Clyde's record home attendance to this day. Financial pressures led to the club relinquishing ownership of the stadium in 1935, selling it their former tenants, the Greyhound Racing Association. This arrangement continued satisfactorily for over 50 years until the GRA announced redevelopment plans for the stadium and gave Clyde notice to quit in 1986.\n\n===Broadwood Stadium===\nBroadwood is a football stadium and multi-use community sports complex situated in [[Cumbernauld]], [[North Lanarkshire]], Scotland. In 1990, Clyde had secured an agreement to move into a stadium well built in the new town of Cumbernauld, which due to shifting population patterns was by now one of the larger settlements in Scotland without a senior football team.  The new all-seater venue would not be ready until 1994 for Clyde to move to forever.\n\nClyde moved into [[Broadwood Stadium|Broadwood]] midway through the [[1994\u201395 in Scottish football|1994\u201395]] season. Broadwood has hosted [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]] matches and four [[Scottish League Challenge Cup|Scottish Challenge Cup]] finals in the past. Broadwood was also home to [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrie]] for four seasons from 1994\u201398 and [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers reserves]] for a while.\n\nOn 9 December 2010, Clyde had informed their landlords at North Lanarkshire Council (NL Leisure) of their intention to relinquish their lease on Broadwood and move elsewhere.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/clyde/9276400.stm|title=Clyde planning to leave Broadwood|author=|date=10 December 2010|publisher=|accessdate=15 March 2018|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Furthermore, on 19 October 2011, Clyde revealed that they were investigating the possibility of a move to [[East Kilbride]], the largest town in Scotland without a senior football team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/15378782|title=Clyde investigate move to new stadium in East Kilbride|author=|date=20 October 2011|publisher=|accessdate=15 March 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Another option was to move back to Rutherglen and develop the Clyde Gateway Stadium in a ground-sharing agreement. This had received approval from current tenants [[Rutherglen Glencairn F.C.|Rutherglen Glencairn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2012/09/17/4195/|title=Rutherglen Approve Proposal - 17 Sep 2012 - News - Clyde Football Club|author=|date=|website=Official Clyde Football Club Website|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Ground shares===\nAfter quitting Shawfield in 1986, the club investigated several local options. Clyde secured an agreement with arch-rivals [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] to share their ground [[Firhill Stadium|Firhill]] for five seasons until 1991. Despite reaching an agreement to move into Broadwood in 1990, it would not be until 1994 when the ground was ready, so Clyde shared with [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Accies]] at their [[Douglas Park]] for a further three seasons.\n[[File: Firhill at night.jpg|thumbnail|[[Firhill Stadium|Firhill]], home of [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]], which has previously been used by Clyde]]\n\nThe club negotiated a groundshare with [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa]] to use [[Recreation Park, Alloa|Recreation Park]] for the club's first home game of the [[2012\u201313 Clyde F.C. season|2012\u201313]] season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Ramsden Cup Draw|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2012/06/12/4128/|publisher=clydefc.co.uk|date=12 June 2012|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref> a first round [[2012\u201313 Scottish Challenge Cup|Challenge Cup]] match against [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Clyde 0\u20131 Partick Thistle|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2012/07/28/4154/|publisher=clydefc.co.uk|date=28 July 2012|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref> During pre-season work had begun at Broadwood to replace the grass pitch with an artificial surface ([[astroturf]])<ref>{{cite news|title=Work Begins at Broadwoad|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2012/06/05/4120/|publisher=clydefc.co.uk|date=5 June 2012|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref> and the pitch was not finished in time for their first home match of the season. Clyde were confident that the pitch would be completed and all the details finalised for the club's first home league match of the season in time for the visit of [[Peterhead F.C.|Peterhead]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pitch on Schedule|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2012/07/24/4148/|publisher=clydefc.co.uk|date=24 July 2012|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref> The match was switched to Recreation Park for the second successive home game after a pitch inspection carried out earlier in the week by the [[Scottish Football League|SFL]] decided that the pitch was not at the stage of completion as expected.<ref>{{cite news|title=Match Switched to Alloa|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2012/08/14/4168/|publisher=clydefc.co.uk|date=14 August 2012|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref> Installation of the new surface was completed in time for the club's next home match of the league season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Broadwood Ready for Action|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2012/08/26/4180/|publisher=clydefc.co.uk|date=26 August 2012|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Supporters==\n\nThe supporters' fiercest rivalry is with [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]], given that the two clubs are both of smaller stature to that of [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]. However, given the success and promotion of Partick Thistle to the [[Scottish Premiership]], and Clyde's recent relegation to the [[Scottish League Two]], such derby games have become a rarity in past years.\n\nThe number of years Clyde spent without a permanent home of their own led to the fans identifying themselves as the ''[[Scottish Gypsy and Traveller groups|Gypsy]] Army''.\n\nThe Clyde Supporters Social Club on [[Rutherglen|Rutherglen Main Street]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Clyde Supporters Social Club in Glasgow|url=http://www.thetimenow.com/united_kingdom/glasgow/clubs_and_associations-371/clyde_supporters_social_club-956603|publisher=thetimenow.com|accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref> burned down in the early 2000s and has never been rebuilt or re-opened.<ref>{{cite web|title=Clyde Supporters Club|url=http://www.reigart.com/experience/city-centre/clyde-supporters-club?slide=3|publisher=reigart.com|accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref> There was also a Supporters Club located in [[Kirkintilloch]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Thistle Clash is a Cruise for Clyde|url=http://www.kirkintilloch-herald.co.uk/sport/thistle-clash-is-a-cruise-for-clyde-1-361149|publisher=kirkintilloch-herald.co.uk|date=11 September 2001|accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Clyde Supporters' Trust got formed during season 2003\u201304. A group of fans became aware of the club's severe financial problems as Billy Carmichael's reign as chairman came to an end. It was formed in time to save the club and keep it in the supporter's hands in a time that coincided with Clyde's failure to gain promotion and the chairman looking to sell his majority shareholding.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Supporters' Trust|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/supporters-trust/history/|publisher=clydefc.co.uk|accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the past the Supporters' Trust has financed the signings of players such as [[John Potter (footballer)|John Potter]] and [[Tom Brighton]], and retaining the signatures of players such as [[Neil McGregor]] and [[David Hutton (footballer born 1985)|David Hutton]].\n\nThe Clyde supporters also run their own supporters team called Bully Wee United.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bully Wee United|url=http://www.clubwebsite.co.uk/bullyweeunited/134943/Home|publisher=clubwebsite.co.uk/bullyweeunited|accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref> Bully Wee United are recognised as the official supporters team of Clyde and represent the club in the IFA League<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internetfootball.org.uk/ifa-competitions/ifa-league/|title=IFA League - Internet Football Association|author=|date=|website=www.internetfootball.org.uk|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref> with matches well played Saturday mornings. Matches are normally against the supporter's teams of the opposition facing the first team on the same day. Bully Wee United is unique in most Scottish supporters teams as they operate a strict policy that only Clyde supporters may play for the team. Players must attend a minimum number of Clyde games over a season. Clyde is also represented in the Scottish Central Amateur League by another supporters team named Broadwood Clyde. They got formed in 1994. They were crowned SSFL Division One league champions in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bully Wee Fans Crowned The Best in Scotland|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2005/08/11/1472/|publisher=clydefc.co.uk|date=11 August 2005|accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref> They also won the SSFL League Cup in 2004 and SSFL Inter-Division Cup in 2003 making them the most successful Clyde supporters team.<ref>{{cite web|title=Broadwood Clyde Lift League Cup|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2004/07/20/1015/|publisher=clydefc.co.uk|date=20 July 2004|accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref> Broadwood Clyde play their homes games at Ravenswood in Cumbernauld on Sunday afternoons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Broadwood Clyde|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=fr&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.broadwood-clyde.co.uk%2F|publisher=broadwood-clyde.co.uk|accessdate=5 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Nickname==\nThe club's nickname, \"The Bully Wee\", is of uncertain origin although the club themselves have advanced three theories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/club/history/origins/|title=Origins - History - Club - Clyde Football Club|author=|date=|website=Official Clyde Football Club Website|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe first suggests that the clubs and supporters and perhaps players mainly came from [[Bridgeton, Glasgow]], a tight working-class area whose inhabitants had a reputation as \"wee bullies\", with this becoming transposed as the Bully Wee.\n\nAlternatively, it is also claimed that it comes from around 1900 when a group of French supporters paid a visit to Barrowfield and, upon the scoring of a disputed goal, were heard to remark  \"But il'y, oui?\" or \"Their goal, yes\". Supporters listened to this unfamiliar phrase as \"Bully Wee\", and the name stuck.\n\nFinally the third theory, and the one accepted by the club as the most plausible, links the term to the old Victorian idiom \"bully\" meaning first-rate or high standard and suggests that Clyde, a small club, would have been regularly referred to as \"Bully Wee Clyde\", with the first two words eventually becoming the standalone nickname.\n\n==Rivalries==\nOriginally from Glasgow, Clyde developed local rivalries with other teams from in and around the city including [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] and [[Queen's Park F.C.|Queen's Park]] and from previous years now-defunct teams like [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]] and [[Third Lanark F.C.|Third Lanark]]. Any game between any of these two would be known as a [[Local derbies in the United Kingdom#Senior football|Glasgow derby]].\n\nIt got well said that Partick Thistle is who the Bully Wee's pivotal derby is within this case. The Clyde vs Thistle derby was previously a fierce battle between two of Glasgow's smaller clubs, in comparison to the [[Old Firm]]. However, due to Partick Thistle's promotion to Scotland's highest professional league, the [[Scottish Premiership]], and Clyde's recent relegations to the lower leagues, such meetings between the two clubs are no longer so common.\n\nIn recent times, the rivalry got intensified when Thistle became Clyde's landlords at [[Firhill Stadium|Firhill]] for five years. The decision to groundshare with Thistle was never really accepted by either Clyde or Thistle supporters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Partick Thistle|url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/950-The-five-minute.../2926-partick-thistle|publisher=[[When Saturday Comes]]|date=1 April 2002|accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nFrom late 2010 onwards, Clyde has been looking to leave [[Broadwood Stadium|Broadwood]] for a new home. In early 2012, Partick Thistle chairman David Beattie said he welcome a deal to see Clyde groundshare at Firhill once more. He said it would reignite the Glasgow-rivalry and would benefit both clubs. \"I am all for ground-sharing, and Clyde are traditionally a Glasgow club, and the healthy rivalry between ourselves and the Bully Wee is historical\".<ref>{{cite news|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419133313/http://www.theglaswegian.co.uk/football/partick-thistle-fc/partick-thistle-news/2012/03/22/firhill-groundshare-would-add-welcome-edge-to-partick-thistle-clyde-rivalry-says-jags-chief-beattie-102692-23797620/|archivedate=19 April 2012|title=Firhill groundshare would add welcome edge to Partick Thistle \u2013 Clyde rivalry, says Jags chief Beattie|url=http://www.theglaswegian.co.uk/football/partick-thistle-fc/partick-thistle-news/2012/03/22/firhill-groundshare-would-add-welcome-edge-to-partick-thistle-clyde-rivalry-says-jags-chief-beattie-102692-23797620/|publisher=theglaswegian.co.uk|date=22 March 2012|accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nShortly after [[Jamie Mitchell (footballer)|Jamie Mitchell]] left Clyde for the [[Firhill Stadium|Firhill]] club in 2002, Mitchell stated well into an interview he could not believe the abuse he got for moving clubs and that moving to Thistle made matters worse. He also referred to getting \"the [[Maurice Johnston (footballer)|Mo Johnston]] treatment\" and that he no idea how intense the rivalry between both clubs was.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jamie Mitchell can't believe fans reactions|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2002/05/19/131/|publisher=clydefc.co.uk|date=19 May 2002|accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref> Former Partick Thistle midfielder [[Scott Chaplain]], once a signing target of Clyde before he arrived at Firhill spoke of the \"competitive edges to those particular matches\" after playing in the fixture.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2007/11/02/2251/|title=From the Other Side|work=Clyde FC|date=2 November 2007|accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn recent times a rivalry has developed with [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+Anti-Billy+brigade's+letting+the+Clyde+down+says...-a0137611707|title=Anti-Billy brigade's letting the Clyde down says brassed-off Balmer|work=Daily Record|via=[[TheFreeDictionary.com#TheFreeLibrary.com|TheFreeLibrary]]|date=17 October 2005|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/alan-pattullo-best-fans-in-world-it-doesn-t-look-like-it-1-800863|title=Best Fans in the World, Doesn't look like it|work=The Scotsman|date=22 April 2010|accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> In recent seasons, Queen's Park have become the clubs natural rivals as both club have been competing in the same division, the fourth tier of Scottish football since 2010. Clyde have not been in the same division as Thistle or Accies since 2009.\n\n==The Clyde View==\nThe '''''Clyde View''''' is Clyde's official matchday programme. It won the Scottish Programme of the Year Award every season from 1995\u201396 to 2006\u201307, and again in 2008\u201309. It also won the Scottish Divisional Programme of the Year Award every season from 1991\u201392 to 2011\u201312. It won the inaugural Scottish Divisional Programme Best Design of the Year Award for season 2011\u201312.<ref>{{cite web| URL = http://www.pmfc.co.uk/html/scotsawards.html|title = Programme of the Year Awards|publisher = PM Publications|accessdate = 22 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2011/04/06/3853/|title = More Success for the Clyde View|publisher = clydefc.co.uk|date = 6 April 2012|accessdate = 22 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn Wirrel's UK Programme of the Year, it achieved a top ten finish on three consecutive occasions from 2002\u201303 to 2004\u201305; 8th (2002\u201303), 6th (2003\u201304) and 5th (2004\u201305).<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2003/07/02/611/|title = Award For Cv|publisher = clydefc.co.uk|date = 2 July 2003|accessdate = 27 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2004/05/25/976/|title = Clyde View Does It Again|publisher = clydefc.co.uk|date = 25 May 2004|accessdate = 27 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2005/05/31/1395/|title = Clyde View Earns More Awards|publisher = clydefc.co.uk|date = 31 May 2005|accessdate = 27 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Managers==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*[[Walter Jack]] (1905\u20131909)\n*[[Frank Thompson (Irish footballer)|Frank Thompson]] (1922\u20131934)\n*Russell Moreland (1934\u20131937)\n*[[Paddy Travers]] (1938\u20131954)\n*[[Johnny Haddow]] (1954\u20131963)\n*[[John Prentice (footballer born 1926)|John Prentice]] (1963\u20131966)\n*[[David White (Scottish footballer)|Davie White]] (1966\u20131967)\n*[[Archie Wright]] (1967)\n*[[Archie Robertson (Scottish footballer)|Archie Robertson]] (1968\u20131973)\n*[[Stan Anderson (Scottish footballer)|Stan Anderson]] (1973\u20131976)\n*Mike Clinton (1976\u20131977)\n*[[Billy McNeill]] (1977)\n*[[Craig Brown (footballer born 1940)|Craig Brown]] (1977\u20131987)\n*[[John Clark (footballer born 1941)|John Clark]] (1987\u20131992)\n*[[Alex Smith (footballer born 1939)|Alex Smith]] (1992\u20131996)\n*[[Gardner Speirs]] (1996\u20131998)\n*Ronnie McDonald (1998)\n*[[Allan Maitland]] (1998\u20132002)\n*[[Alan Kernaghan]] (2002\u20132004)\n*[[Billy Reid (footballer, born 1963)|Billy Reid]] (2004\u20132005)\n*[[Graham Roberts (footballer)|Graham Roberts]] (2005\u20132006)\n*[[Joe Miller (footballer)|Joe Miller]] (2006\u20132007)\n*[[Colin Hendry]] (2007\u20132008)\n*[[John Brown (footballer born 1962)|John Brown]] (2008\u20132009)\n*[[John McCormack (footballer, born 1955)|John McCormack]] (2009\u20132010)\n*[[Stuart Millar]] (2010\u20132011)\n*[[Jim Duffy (footballer)|Jim Duffy]] (2011\u20132014)\n*[[Barry Ferguson]] (2014\u20132017)\n*[[Jim Chapman (footballer)|Jim Chapman]] (2017)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41822366 |title=Clyde part with manager Jim Chapman after poor run of results |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=31 October 2017 |accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Danny Lennon]] (2017\u2013present)\n}}\n\n==First-team squad==\n{{updated|31 January 2020<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.clydefc.co.uk/team/profiles/ |title=2019\u201320 Clyde FC squad |website=Clyde FC |accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=Michael McGee|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[David Mitchell (footballer, born 1990)|David Mitchell]]|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[Barry Cuddihy]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[Kieran Duffie]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=Craig Howie|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[Tom Lang]]|pos=DF|other=on loan from [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[Adam Livingstone]]|pos=DF|other=on loan from [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=Michael McMullin|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[Martin McNiff]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=Scott Rumsby|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[Ray Grant]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[Chris Johnston (footballer)|Chris Johnston]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=Mark Lamont|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[Ally Love]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=Ross Lyon|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=Chris McStay|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[John Rankin (footballer)|John Rankin]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[Gregg Wylde]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[Ross Cunningham]]|pos=FW|other=on loan from [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Accies]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=Declan Fitzpatrick|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[David Goodwillie]]|pos=FW|other=[[captain (association football)|captain]]}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=SCO|name=[[Darren Smith (footballer, born 1988)|Darren Lee Smith]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no=|nat=NOR|name=Kristoffer Syvertsen|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs end}}\n<!--===On loan===\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs end}}-->\n\n==Club officials==\n\n===Board===\n*'''Chairman:''' ''Vacant''\n*'''Vice Chairman and Operations Director:''' John Taylor\n*'''Commercial and Corporate Major Donor Relations Director:''' David MacPherson\n*'''Income Generation Director:''' Gordon Nisbet\n*'''Head of Strategy and Match Secretary:''' Gordon Thomson\n*'''Head of Governance and Company Secretary:''' Claire Thornber\n*'''Associate Directors:''' \n**David Alexander\n**Ian Fitzpatrick\n**Charlie Lowrie\n\n===Coaching staff===\n*'''Manager:''' [[Danny Lennon]]\n*'''Assistant Manager:''' [[Allan Moore]]\n*'''Goalkeeping Coach:''' Chris Fahey\n*'''Video Analyst:''' Andy Muir\n*'''Kitmen:''' Joe Hayes & Andy Quinn\n*'''Head of Physiotherapy:''' Iain McKinlay\n*'''Sports Therapist:''' Alannah MacPherson\n\n==Reserve and Youth Teams==\n===Reserve League Cup===\nClyde put together a reserve team for the [[Scottish Football League|SFL's]] Reserve League Cup competition, which included a mixture of first team fringe players and youngsters.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2008/09/10/2864/|title = Reserve League Cup 2008\u201309|publisher = Clyde FC|date = 10 September 2008|accessdate = 10 June 2009}}</ref> The club won the Reserve League Cup for the first time in May 2008. They defeated [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]] 4\u20131 on their own ground at [[Almondvale]] with [[Dave McKay (footballer)|Dave McKay]] scoring all four goals for Clyde.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2008/05/05/2717/|title = McKay fires Clyde to Reserve Trophy|publisher = Clyde FC|date = 5 May 2008|accessdate = 10 June 2009}}</ref> It was the team's first piece of silverware at reserve level for twenty years. The following season the club were knocked out by [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] in the semi-finals losing 3\u20130 in [[Dingwall]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Reserves Crash Out|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2009/05/04/3149/|publisher=Clyde FC|date=4 May 2009|accessdate=29 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Reserve team history===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!League\n!Seasons\n|-\n|Scottish Football Federation||1898-99\n|-\n|Scottish Football Alliance||1896-97, 1919\u201321, 1937\u201338, 1939\u201340, 1956\u201357\n|-\n|Scottish Reserve League||1909-11, 1913\u201315, 1938\u201339, 1945\u201349, 1955\u201356, 1957\u201361, 1962\u201363, 1964\u201365, 1969\u201372, 1973\u201375\n|-\n|Scottish C Division South & West||1949-55\n|-\n|Combined Reserve Football League||1961-62, 1963\u201364, 1975\u201376\n|-\n|Scottish Reserve League (West)||1979-81, 1983\u201393, 1994\u201397, 1998-2001\n|-\n|Scottish Reserve League (West 'A')||1993-94\n|}\n\n===='A' Team====\nIt was common from the beginning of reserve football for the majority of club's reserve teams (second XI's) to go by the tag \u2018A\u2019 or sometimes \u2018B\u2019 or even \u2018C\u2019 if a club had more than one reserve side. It wasn't until after the formation of the new Scottish Reserve League in 1955 that today's reserve teams go by the actual tag \u2018reserves\u2019 and have done since 1957.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reserve Football (Overview 1881-date)|url=http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/reserves.htm|publisher=Scottish-Football-Historical-Archives|accessdate=30 August|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117022532/http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/reserves.htm|archive-date=17 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1881-82 season, Clyde reached the semi-finals of the Scottish 2nd XI Cup in the competitions the first season. In 1896-97 they reached their first 'major' cup final, the Scottish 2nd XI Cup final eventually losing 4-0 to [[Hearts of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]]. After reaching the semi-finals again in 1905-06, they were thwarted by arch-rivals [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] this time.\n\nThe club first joined the Scottish Reserve League in 1909-10 and found the first few years of competing in the league though. It wasn't until the 1913-14 season when they made their mark when they lost 1-0 at Hearts in a league decider for the Reserve League title. It meant that the club missed out on a unique [[Double (association football)|League and Cup double]] after they captured the Scottish 2nd XI Cup for the first time that season. They dispatched of [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]  in the final over two legs (1-1 away and 3-1 at home). They successfully defended the Scottish 2nd XI Cup the following season when Clyde overcame Falkirk in the final over two legs (2-1 loss away and a 3-1 home win).\n\nTheir third and final Scottish 2nd XI Cup triumph came in 1941-42. It would be the team's last 'major' cup success for the next sixty-six years. In 1945-46 they reached their last Scottish 2nd XI Cup final losing to Hibs, after a superb 6-2 derby victory over arch-rivals [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] in the semifinals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Second Eleven Cup|url=http://www.scottishleague.net/forum/viewtopic.php?f=3&t=2954|publisher=scottishleague.net|accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Scottish Reserve League merged with the [[List of winners of the Scottish Second Division and predecessors|Scottish C Division]] ([[Scottish football league system|third tier]]) for the [[1949\u201350 in Scottish football|1949\u201350]] season creating two regionalised divisions (South/West and North/East) with Clyde entering a reserve team in the South & West region. The club was crowned champions in [[1949\u201350 in Scottish football|1949\u201350]] and they retained their title in [[1950\u201351 in Scottish football|1950\u201351]]. Despite successive titles, there was no promotion as only first teams could gain promotion to Division B. As reserve teams got excluded from the [[Scottish League Cup]], the C Division had their League Cup. Clyde couldn't quite match the success in the cup that they had in the league as they never won the competition. The best they could manage were semi-final appearances in 1951-52<ref>{{cite web|title=C Division & League Cup, dates results & final tables 1951-52|url=http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/cdiv5152.htm|publisher=Scottish-Football-Historical-Archives|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> and in 1953-54.<ref>{{cite web|title=C Division & League Cup, dates results & final tables 1953-54|url=http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/cdiv5354.htm|publisher=Scottish-Football-Historical-Archives|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n====League restructuring====\nAfter both regional C Divisions got scrapped in June 1955, a new Scottish Reserve League started up. The new Reserve League was an exclusively all First Division league (a mirror image of the senior league) and all Second Division clubs' reserve sides got excluded from joining. There were several seasons when not all clubs took part. As for teams who were turned away or excluded from joining, they joined various [[supplementary football leagues|supplementary leagues]] over the next few years.\n\nFor the first few seasons between 1955 and 1960, Clyde regularly finished quite high up the table or at least in a mid-table position. From then onwards in the seasons they spent in the league, the team were often at the wrong end of the table.\n\nIn one of the seasons that Clyde didn't participate in the Reserve League, they joined the [[Combined Reserve Football League|Combined Reserve League]] for a single season in 1961\u201362. Due to the small number of teams involved, the competition got split into an Autumn Series and Spring Series. The club won the Autumn Series and finished second overall in the Combined Table.\n\nJust like Clyde's first team, whose last spell in the Scottish top flight came in 1974\u201375, the same fate happened to their reserve team following a further league restructure at senior and reserve level. The Reserve League set-up changed again in 1975 after a reorganisation of the 'senior' Scottish League into [[Scottish football league system|Premier-First-Second Divisions]]. The new Premier Reserve League was a mirror image of the new [[Scottish Football League Premier Division|Scottish Premier Division]] in terms of membership. Lower league clubs used varying set-ups such as East-West sections and midweek competitions. In later games, clubs didn't always participate as running a reserve side became expensive.\n\nIt wasn't until season 1979\u201380 when Clyde gained membership to re-enter a reserve team in the Scottish Reserve League. They got placed in the regional West division. Finishing bottom in their first season, it was a further two seasons before they returned. They fared much better during the 1987\u201388 season when they won the division. It proved to be a one-off, though. Season 2000\u201301 was Clyde's last in the West Reserves League eventually before all reserves leagues got scrapped after season 2007\u201308.\n\n===Youth teams===\nClyde ran youth teams at under-20, under-17, under-15, under-14, under-13, under-12 and under-11 level.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.clydefc.co.uk/youth/|title = Youth Development|publisher = Clyde FC|accessdate = 30 July 2015}}</ref> There was an under-18 team until 2003, when it made way for under-17 and under-19 teams.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2003/07/19/627/|title=Youth Team News|publisher=Clyde FC|date=19 July 2003|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref> The under-20 team replaced the under-19 team in 2014. The club also run Football Schools in [[Cumbernauld]] (since 2006) and [[Glasgow Southside (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Southside]] (since 2008).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/community/football/ | title=The Official Community Programme of Clyde FC | publisher=Clyde FC | accessdate=30 July 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824191553/http://www.clydefc.co.uk/community/football/ | archive-date=24 August 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/community/football/cumbernauld/ | title=Community Football \u2013 Cumbernauld Branch | publisher=Clyde FC | accessdate=30 July 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715031355/http://www.clydefc.co.uk/community/football/cumbernauld/ | archive-date=15 July 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/community/football/southside/ | title=Community Football \u2013 Glasgow Southside Branch | publisher=Clyde FC | accessdate=30 July 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150824191558/http://www.clydefc.co.uk/community/football/southside/ | archive-date=24 August 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Both schools have since been awarded the SFA Quality Mark Award at Standard level and then at Development Level.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2011/12/19/4022/|title=Southside School Achieves Quality Mark|publisher=Clyde FC|date=19 December 2011|accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2013/03/06/4320/|title=SFA Award for Community Branch|publisher=Clyde FC|date=6 March 2013|accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe club were forced to scrap their youth academy from under 11 to under 17 levels in 2015 citing a reduction in funding from the [[Scottish Football Association|Scottish FA]], with the under-20 side the only youth team remaining, which acts as a feeder to the first team for young players.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33075792 | title=Clyde scrap youth academy | work=BBC Sport | date=10 June 2015 | accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe under-17 team reached the final of their Scottish Youth Cup in 2004 losing 4\u20131 on penalties to [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Accies]] at [[New Douglas Park]] despite scoring in stoppage time of extra time to make it 1\u20131.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2004/05/18/970/#.Vbqq59FRHIU | title=Sore Defeat For Hillcoat'S Men | publisher=Clyde FC| date=18 May 2004 | accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> Both youth teams at under-19 and under-17 level reached the semi-finals of their Scottish Youth Cups in 2006.<ref>{{cite news|title=19's Defeated|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2006/05/06/1750/|publisher=Clyde FC|date=6 May 2006|accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=17S Fail To Progress|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2006/05/13/1758/|publisher=Clyde FC|date=13 May 2006|accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> The under-19 side finished runners-up to [[Celtic F.C. Reserve and Youth squads|Celtic]] in the inaugural SPFL under-19 league in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spfl.co.uk/reserve-and-youth/u19-league-table/|title=SPFL Under-19 League 2013\u201314|publisher=SPFL|accessdate=5 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe under-19 team travelled to the [[Netherlands]] in 2003, taking part in a highly rated youth football programme called the ''Leonardo Project'' hosted by [[FC Dordrecht]]. They played three times against an under-19 team of the hosts, which contained Dutch youth internationalists, winning two and drawing one.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2003/08/03/643/|title=Youngsters Win Abroad|publisher=Clyde FC|date=3 August 2003|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2003/08/10/654/|title=Update From Holland|publisher=Clyde FC|date=10 August 2003|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref> In the third match, the opposition was made up of reserves and first team fringe players. They followed this up with a win over local [[amateur football|amateur]] team [[vv Capelle]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2003/08/14/661/|title=Update From Holland 2|publisher=Clyde FC|date=14 August 2003|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref> and a narrow defeat to a youthful [[FC Utrecht]] team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2003/08/20/671/|title=Youngster Return From Holland|publisher=Clyde FC|date=20 August 2003|accessdate=6 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Lanarkshire FA started the Lanarkshire Supercounty Trophy for the under-17 teams of the four senior Lanarkshire clubs in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.motherwelltimes.co.uk/sport/local-sport/youth-football-teams-all-set-for-super-cup-1-3121635|title=Youth football teams all set for Super cup|publisher=Motherwell Times|date=2 October 2013|accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref> In its first year Clyde defeated Motherwell in the semi-final,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2013/12/12/4519/|title=Under-17s Set for County Final|publisher=Clyde FC|date=12 December 2013|accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref> but lost to [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Accies]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/hamilton-accies-win-lanarkshire-supercounty-2944336|title=Accies win Lanarkshire Supercounty Under-17 Trophy|newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|date=19 December 2013|accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom the 2018\u201319 season, Clyde have replaced their Under 20 side with a project alongside [[North Lanarkshire Council]] called Project Braver, which will see young players play at youth level with a chance to progress to the first team, alongside providing further education or apprenticeship opportunities for the players.\n\n====Graduates====\nGraduates of the youth team who have gone on to play for the first team since moving to [[Broadwood Stadium]] include:\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-5}}\n* Jamie Prunty\n* Martin O'Neill\n* [[Craig McEwan (footballer)|Craig McEwan]]\n* [[Brian Carrigan]]\n* Paul Brownlie\n* Michael O'Neill\n* Paul Campbell\n* John McLay\n* Stuart Coleman\n* Lorn Gibson\n* Gary McPhee\n{{col-5}}\n* Gary Robertson\n* [[Paul Stewart (footballer born 1979)|Paul Stewart]]\n* [[Paul Hay]]\n* [[Graham McGhee]]\n* [[Mark Gilhaney]]\n* [[Paul Doyle (footballer)|Paul Doyle]]\n* [[Billy Reid (footballer, born 1986)|Billy Reid Jnr.]]\n* [[John Baird (footballer, born 1985)|John Baird]]\n* Charlie Clark\n* [[Robert Halliday (footballer)|Robert Halliday]]\n* [[Craig Bryson]]\n{{col-5}}\n* [[David Greenhill]]\n* [[Graeme McCracken]]\n* [[Kevin Bradley (Scottish footballer)|Kevin Bradley]]\n* [[John Paul McKeever]]\n* [[Robert Harris (footballer)|Robert Harris]]\n* [[Sean McKenna (footballer)|Sean McKenna]]\n* [[Ruari MacLennan]]\n* [[David McGowan (footballer)|David McGowan]]\n* [[Michael Doherty (footballer)|Michael Doherty]]\n* [[Stephen Connolly]]\n* [[Roddy MacLennan]]\n{{col-5}}\n* [[Jordan Murch]]\n* [[Connor Stevenson]]\n* Jordan Allan\n* [[Steven Howarth]]\n* Darren Walker\n* Connor Cassidy\n* Kevin Higgins\n* Daniel Fitzpatrick\n* Jack Sloss\n* Drew Ramsay\n* Kieran Daw\n{{col-5}}\n* Grant Dickie\n* Scott Ferguson \n* Fraser McGhee\n* Gordon Young \n* William Robb\n{{col-end}}\n\n[[Scotland national football team|Scottish internationals]] [[Pat Nevin]], [[Steve Archibald]] and [[Ian Ferguson (footballer born 1967)|Ian Ferguson]] also came through the Clyde youth system.\n\n==Hall of Fame==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n;'''Hall of Fame'''\n*The Dunn family (2011)<ref name=2011HOF>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2011/09/28/3960/ | title=Clyde FC Hall of Fame | publisher=Clyde FC | date=28 October 2011 | accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|SCO}} [[George Herd]] (2011)<ref name=2011HOF/>\n*{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Davie Laing]] (2011)<ref name=2011HOF/>\n*{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Tommy McCulloch (footballer, born 1934)|Tommy McCulloch]] (2011)<ref name=2011HOF/>\n*{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Pat Nevin]] (2011)<ref name=2011HOF/>\n*{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Craig Brown (footballer born 1940)|Craig Brown]] (2012)<ref name=2012HOF>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2012/09/30/4207/ | title=Hall of Dinner 2012 | publisher=Clyde FC | date=30 September 2012 | accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=2012HOF2>{{cite web | url=http://www.clydefc.co.uk/news/2012/10/25/4224/ | title=Rough Confirmed for Dinner | publisher=Clyde FC | date