 School]].\n\n== Cities and towns ==\nThe Central West includes two cities: [[Bathurst, New South Wales|Bathurst]] and [[Orange, New South Wales|Orange]]; four large towns: [[Cowra, New South Wales|Cowra]], [[Mudgee]], [[Parkes, New South Wales|Parkes]] and [[Lithgow, New South Wales|Lithgow]]; smaller centres, such as [[Oberon, New South Wales|Oberon]] and [[Forbes, New South Wales|Forbes]]; and small towns and villages such as [[Canowindra, New South Wales|Canowindra]], [[Cudal, New South Wales|Cudal]], [[Molong, New South Wales|Molong]], [[Grenfell, New South Wales|Grenfell]], [[West Wyalong, New South Wales|West Wyalong]], [[Portland, New South Wales|Portland]], [[Wallerawang]], [[Condobolin, New South Wales|Condobolin]] and [[Eugowra, New South Wales|Eugowra]].\n\n===Demography and area===\nThe following [[Local government areas of New South Wales|local government areas]] are contained within the region:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|+Population by Local Government Area\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Central West rank\n! scope=\"col\" | Local Government Area\n! scope=\"col\" | Population 30 June  2016<ref name=\"3218.0\">{{cite web |publisher=Australian Bureau of Statistics |title=3218.0 \u2013 Regional Population Growth, Australia, 2016 |url=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305015843/http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/allprimarymainfeatures/797F86DBD192B8F8CA2568A9001393CD?opendocument# |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" | 10 year growth rate\n! scope=\"col\" | Population density (people/km<sup>2</sup>)\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 1\n| [[Bathurst Regional Council]]\n| 42,389\n| 14.8\n| 11.1\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 2\n| [[City of Orange (New South Wales)|Orange City]]\n| 41,384\n| 13.8\n| 145.6\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 3\n| [[Mid-Western Regional Council]]\n| 24,569\n| 13.5\n| 2.8\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 4\n| [[City of Lithgow|City of Lithgow Council]]\n| 21,524\n| 6.6\n| 4.8\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 7\n| [[Parkes Shire|Parkes Shire Council]]\n| 14,946\n| 2.4\n| 2.5\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 8\n| [[Cabonne Shire Council|Cabonne Shire]]\n| 13,625\n| 7.8\n| 2.3\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 9\n| [[Cowra Shire Council|Cowra Shire]]\n| 12,673\n| -0.6\n| 4.5\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 10\n| [[Forbes Shire Council|Forbes Shire]]\n| 9,808\n| 2.8\n| 2.1\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 11\n| [[Blayney Shire Council|Blayney Shire]]\n| 7,418\n| 10.0\n| 4.9\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 12\n| [[Lachlan Shire Council|Lachlan Shire]]\n| 6,352\n| -7.0\n| 0.4\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 13\n| [[Bland Shire Council|Bland Shire]]\n| 6,031\n| -2.9\n| 0.7\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 14\n| [[Oberon Council|Oberon Shire]]\n| 5,399\n| 4.2\n| 1.5\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | 15\n| [[Weddin Shire Council|Weddin Shire]]\n| 3,692\n| -0.8\n| 1.1\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Central West\n! style=\"text-align:right\" | 209,810\n! style=\"text-align:right\" | 8.5\n! style=\"text-align:right\" | 3.0\n|}\n\n== Terrain ==\nThe Central West's east is higher, wetter and hillier and supports orchards, [[vineyard]]s, vegetable-growing and pastoralism. The west is flatter and drier and supports grain crops and pastoralism.\n\n== Major highways ==\nThe Central West region is traversed by the [[Great Western Highway]], the [[Mid-Western Highway]], the [[Mitchell Highway]], the [[Newell Highway]] and the [[Castlereagh Highway]].\n\n== Media ==\nThe Central West has several radio stations, including 97.9 2LVR (a community radio station), 105.1 [[2GZ|2GZFM]], 105.9 [[Star FM]], 107.9 [[Move FM]], 107.5 Community Radio, 103.5 [[Rhema FM]] and [[2EL|1089AM]] \u2014 a commercial station that gets most of its programming from [[2SM]] in Sydney. Other electronic media are represented by the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] with both television and radio broadcasting; and by television stations [[Prime7]], [[WIN Television|WIN]], and [[Southern Cross Nine]].\n\nTwo major newspapers are published in the region, the ''[[Central Western Daily]]'' newspaper is published in Orange and the [[The Western Advocate (Bathurst, New South Wales)|Western Advocate]] in Bathurst. Numerous other local papers serve the remaining large towns.\n\n== History ==\nThe Central West area was originally inhabited by the Wiradjuri people. The first white explorer, George Wilson Evans, entered the [[Wyangala#Water resources|Lachlan Valley]] in 1815. He named the area the Oxley Plains after his superior the surveyor-general, John Oxley. In 1817 he deemed the area unfit for white settlement. A Military Depot was established not long after at Soldiers Flat near present-day Billimari. Arthur Ranken and James Sloan, from Bathurst, were amongst the first white settlers on the Lachlan. They moved to the area in 1831.\n\nIn the 1850s many gold prospectors passed through headed for gold fields at Lambing Flat ([[Young, New South Wales|Young]]) and [[Grenfell, New South Wales|Grenfell]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Central West (New South Wales)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091112022439/http://www.bom.gov.au/weather/nsw/nsw-forecast-map.shtml NSW Forecast Areas map]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080905131130/http://www.dlg.nsw.gov.au/dlg/dlghome/dlg_regions.asp?mi=0&ml=8&regiontype=1&region=CW Department of Local Government page for the region] listing links to council pages\n* [http://www.dmoz.org/Regional/Oceania/Australia/New_South_Wales/Regions/Central_West/ \"Open Directory\" listing]\n\n{{Regions of New South Wales |state=autocollapse}}\n\n[[Category:Regions of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Central West (New South Wales)| ]]\n[[Category:Newell Highway]]\n", "name_user": "Snowbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_West_(New_South_Wales)"}
